<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910823-0104</DOCNO><DOCID>910823-0104.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Communications Satellite Corp.:   New Satellite Service Rates   Get Approval From FCC</HL><DATE>08/23/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3C</SO><CO>   CQ</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)</IN><GV>FEDERAL COMMUNICATIONS COMMISSION (FCC)</GV><RE>DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA (DC)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Communications Satellite Corp. said the FederalCommunications Commission approved rates for its newsatellite service Intelsat-K.   The satellite, which will have 16 transponders operatingat 54 megahertz, is expected to be launched in early 1992from Florida. It will be able to provide service to smallearth-station antennas as small as 1.2 meters in diameter andis expected to be used by satellite news gathering, businessTV and data distribution operations based on very smallterminal networks.</LP><TEXT>   The rates include pre-launch discounts of up to 20%. Forexample, the pre-launch rate for a typical five-year leaseconnecting North America and Europe would be $125,955 amonth, compared with the postlaunch rate of $155,500 a month.   Comsat provides satellite capacity and communicationsservices between the U.S. and overseas locations.</TEXT></DOC>